", "prob": 0.9886702299118042, "span": {"begin": 918, "end": 922}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:22937"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SCAP", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9924502372741699, "span": {"begin": 964, "end": 968}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:26958"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "COPII", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.994268536567688, "span": {"begin": 980, "end": 985}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6720"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "SREBPs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9933830499649048, "span": {"begin": 1014, "end": 1020}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002784"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cholesterol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999126136302948, "span": {"begin": 1126, "end": 1137}}], "text": "Insulin-induced gene 1 (INSIG1) is a transmembrane protein in the endoplasmic reticulum membrane (Ouyang et al. 2020). &nbsp;INSIG1 has an important role in lipid synthesis regulation. &nbsp;At low cholesterol levels, INSIG1 has lower binding affinity for SREBP cleavage-activating protein (SCAP), allowing free SCAP to bind to Coat Protein Complex II (COPII; Ouyang et al. 2020). &nbsp;The SCAP-COPII complex enables Sterol Regulatory Element Binding Proteins (SREBPs) to move through the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi, where membrane-bound transcription factor site-1-protease (S1P) and site-2-protease (S2P) enable proteolytic processing that allows SREBPs to enter the nucleus (Yabe et al. 2022; Yang et al. 2022). &nbsp;In the nucleus, SREBP2 increase gene expression for enzymes involved in cholesterol synthesis (Ouyang et al. 2020; Itkonen et al., 2023). &nbsp;At high cholesterol levels, INSIG1 binds to SCAP, competitively inhibiting the ability of SCAP to bind to COPII (Ouyang et al. 2020). &nbsp;SREBPs are retained in the endoplasmic reticulum rather than being transferred to the Golgi, reducing levels of cholesterol synthesis (Ouyang et al. 2020; Itkonen et al., 2023).&nbsp;", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 22:00:53 +0000 2026"}